We are given a permutation problem and a functional equation that depends on a parameter \(k = a_9 - 7\), where \(a_9\) is the ninth element of a permutation of \(1,\dots,9\) satisfying certain sum and square sum conditions. After analyzing the permutation conditions, we find that valid permutations require \(\{a_1, a_4, a_7\} = \{2,5,8\}\) and that the other numbers pair into \(\{1,6\}\), \(\{3,7\}\), \(\{4,9\}\). Among the many valid permutations, the lexicographically smallest one yields \(a_9 = 7\), so \(k = 0\). With \(k=0\), the functional equation becomes \(f((c+1)x + f(y)) = f(x+2y) + 2cx\) for all \(x,y > 0\) and \(c > 0\). Assuming \(f\) is linear, substitution yields \(f(x) = 2x\) as a solution. Further analysis shows that this is the only solution. Thus, the function is \(f(x) = 2x\) for \(x > 0\).

